End of the road for No Bull 5 
By RICK MINTER
Cox News Service

Atlanta -- The Winston No Bull 5 program, which offered 
Winston Cup drivers and fans a chance to win a million dollars 
each at selected races, is no more.

R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Company announced Monday that it is 
discontinuing the program, which began in 1998.

"The Winston No Bull 5 program was a very successful program 
for the Winston brand," said Ned Leary, president of Sports 
Marketing Enterprises, which oversees RJR's racing projects.
"However, we are constantly evaluating the allocation of 
resources. For 2003, the decision has been made to deploy 
those resources in other areas."

Five Winston Cup races each year offered the No Bull 5 bonus. 
The top five finishers in the previous No Bull 5 race were 
eligible for a $1 million bonus if they won the race. Each of 
the five participants was paired with a fan chosen in a random 
drawing. If the fan's driver won the race, the fan also 
collected $1 million. There were at least two winners each 
season.

The decision to drop the bonus program does not affect RJR's 
sponsorship of NASCAR's elite division, the Winston Cup Series.

Rick Minter writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.

