And there's now a minimum weight on the rear axel. 

"Its minimum required weight is 3,400 pounds," said John Darby, 
Winston Cup series director. "So when we weigh the two rear 
wheels together, the weight can not exceed 1,700 pounds." 

NASCAR officials hope the move toward standardization will 
help them make more uniform rules adjustments -- no different 
increments for a Ford, a Pontiac, etc. -- plus, eliminate the 
manufacturer and team squawking that's part of life in the 
Winston Cup garage. 

"It's actually been extremely quiet," said Darby of Tuesday's 
first sessions, which were staffed by 21 NASCAR officials. Most 
cars went through a full morning inspection, mostly for the 
teams' benefit (NASCAR's only test requirement at Daytona is 
that teams run the appropriate restrictor plate). And although 
it's too early to tell the new rules' effects, teams know 
things will be different. 

